                        <interp inst="t18250915-359-victim1815" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-359-off1949 t18250915-359-victim1815"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , his master
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>GEORGE MILLER. I <rs id="t18250915-359-viclabel1951" type="occupation">keep a shoe shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-359-victim1815 t18250915-359-viclabel1951"></join> in <placeName id="t18250915-359-crimeloc1952">Skinner-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-359-crimeloc1952" type="placeName" value="Skinner-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-359-crimeloc1952" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-359-off1949 t18250915-359-crimeloc1952"></join>. These boots are my property; they have my initials on them, but are not made by myself; I had missed three or four dozen pairs at different times previous to the detection of the prisoner.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Was not he in your employ? A. Yes; he lived twice with me - the first time for about five years; the last time he came to me in great distress, being out of work, and I said I would give him 10 s. a week, and the moment he could suit himself better he could leave. He is not a good workman - he was to go on errends; the second time he worked as a clicker - I give my other clickers 24 s. or 25 s, a week.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182509150136"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-359-person1816">
                  CHARLES 
                  PAIN
               <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1816" type="surname" value="PAIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1816" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. These boots were pawned at our shop, by the prisoner, on the 27th of of June. Here are some others, but I did not take them in.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-359-person1817">
                  ABRAHAM 
                  GRIFFITH
               <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1817" type="surname" value="GRIFFITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1817" type="given" value="ABRAHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1817" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner into custody on the 9th of July. I told him what for, and asked him for the duplicates - he said he had destroyed them. I went and searched his lodging; I found some duplicates upon his mother.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. My friends went to Mr. Pain, and asked him if he could swear to these goods - he said No, only by my own confession.</p>
               <p>CHARLES PAIN. I swear I did not say any such thing, nor did I hear the person say so to my recollection. I cannot swear to what passed in conversation with him.</p>
               <p>(Witness for the Defence.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-359-person1818">
                  WILLIAM 
                  WRIGHT
               <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1818" type="surname" value="WRIGHT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1818" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-359-person1818" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live with my father in Fleet-lane. I went one morning with the prisoner's mother, and inquired of Mr. Pain what he had - he said he had the stock of boots, but he could not swear to any boots which the prisoner had pawned.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
